1 L.D. 1894
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 HOUSING AND ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT
4 Reproduced and distributed under the direction of the Clerk of the House.
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1265, L.D. 1894, “An Act to Address
10 Consumer Grocery Pricing Fairness”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'Resolve, to Establish the Commission to Study Consumer Grocery Pricing Fairness'
13 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
14 'Emergency preamble. Whereas, acts and resolves of the Legislature do not
15 become effective until 90 days after adjournment unless enacted as emergencies; and
16 Whereas, this legislation establishes the Commission to Study Consumer Grocery
17 Pricing Fairness; and
18 Whereas, the study must be initiated before the 90-day period expires so that the study
19 may be completed and a report submitted in time for submission to the next legislative
20 session; and
21 Whereas, in the judgment of the Legislature, these facts create an emergency within
22 the meaning of the Constitution of Maine and require the following legislation as
23 immediately necessary for the preservation of the public peace, health and safety; now,
24 therefore, be it
25 Sec. 1. Commission established. Resolved: That the Commission to Study
26 Consumer Grocery Pricing Fairness, referred to in this resolve as "the commission," is
27 established.
28 Sec. 2. Commission membership. Resolved: That, notwithstanding Joint Rule
29 353, the commission consists of 17 voting members and 3 nonvoting members as follows:
30 1. Nine voting members, appointed by the President of the Senate as follows:
31 A. Two members of the Senate, including one member from each of the 2 parties
32 holding the largest number of seats in the Legislature;
Page 1 - 132LR2187(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1265, L.D. 1894
1 B. One member who is a small-scale to medium-scale produce farmer in the State with
2 gross annual sales of less than $300,000;
3 C. One member who is a large-scale produce farmer in the State with gross annual sales
4 of more than $1,000,000;
5 D. One member who is a wholesaler supplier servicing independent grocers in the
6 State;
7 E. One member representing specialty food stores in the State;
8 F. One member who is a representative of a financial institution supporting agriculture
9 and food manufacturing businesses in the State;
10 G. One member who is a food distributor based in the State; and
11 H. One member who is an economist with expertise in agriculture and policy in the
12 State;
13 2. Eight voting members, appointed by the Speaker of the House of Representatives
14 as follows:
15 A. Two members of the House of Representatives, including one member from each
16 of the 2 parties holding the largest number of seats in the Legislature;
17 B. One member who is a processor or manufacturer of locally produced, shelf-stable,
18 packaged food goods;
19 C. One member representing the aquaculture or seafood industry in the State;
20 D. One member who is a representative of an association representing retail and food
21 manufacturers in the State;
22 E. One member representing independent grocers in the State;
23 F. One member who is a national retailer with local-sourcing initiatives; and
24 G. One member representing an economic development organization supporting
25 agriculture and food manufacturing in the State; and
26 3. Three nonvoting members:
27 A. The Commissioner of Economic and Community Development or the
28 commissioner's designee;
29 B. The Commissioner of Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry or the commissioner's
30 designee; and
31 C. The Attorney General or the Attorney General's designee.
32 Sec. 3. Chairs. Resolved: That the first-named Senate member is the Senate chair
33 and the first-named House of Representatives member is the House chair of the
34 commission.
35 Sec. 4. Appointments; convening of commission. Resolved: That all
36 appointments must be made no later than 30 days following the effective date of this
37 resolve. The appointing authorities shall notify the Executive Director of the Legislative
38 Council once all appointments have been completed. After the appointment of all
39 members, the chairs shall call and convene the first meeting of the commission within 45
Page 2 - 132LR2187(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1265, L.D. 1894
410 days. If 30 days or more after the effective date of this resolve a majority of but not all
421 appointments have been made, the chairs may request authority and the Legislative Council
432 may grant authority for the commission to meet and conduct its business.
4 Sec. 5. Duties. Resolved: That the commission shall study the terms and conditions
5 of sale and other conditions of the grocery supply chain in the State that impact product
6 availability and price to consumers, the competitiveness and viability of independent
7 grocery stores, the volume of locally produced products available at retail and market
8 access of producers in the State. As part of its work, the committee may consider the
9 following:
10 1. The growth of so-called food deserts in the State and measures that may be
11 implemented to address or alleviate so-called food deserts;
12 2. Factors in the grocery supply chain that influence affordable access to groceries for
13 residents of the State, that influence competition or concentration in grocery retail in the
14 State and that influence the retail availability of products in the State that are produced in
15 the State; and
16 3. Federal and state antitrust laws and how the enforcement of those laws may affect
17 the growth of so-called food deserts or the grocery store supply chain factors described in
18 subsections 1 and 2.
19 Sec. 6. Staff assistance. Resolved: That the Legislative Council shall provide
20 necessary staffing services to the commission, except that Legislative Council staff support
21 is not authorized when the Legislature is in regular or special session.
22 Sec. 7. Report. Resolved: That, no later than December 3, 2025, the commission
23 shall submit a report that includes its findings and recommendations, including suggested
24 legislation, to the Joint Standing Committee on Housing and Economic Development and
25 to the Joint Standing Committee on Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry. Both
26 committees may report out legislation related to the subject matter of the report to the
27 Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
28 Emergency clause. In view of the emergency cited in the preamble, this legislation
29 takes effect when approved.'
30 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
31 number to read consecutively.
32 SUMMARY
3333 This amendment, which is the majority report of the committee, replaces the bill with
3344 a resolve. It establishes the Commission to Study Consumer Grocery Pricing Fairness,
3355 which is directed to study the terms and conditions of sale and other conditions of the
3366 grocery supply chain in the State that impact product availability and price to consumers,
3377 the competitiveness and viability of independent grocery stores, the volume of locally
3388 produced products available at retail and market access of producers in the State. No later
3399 than December 3, 2025, that commission must submit a report that includes its findings and
4400 recommendations, including suggested legislation, to the Joint Standing Committee on
4411 Housing and Economic Development and to the Joint Standing Committee on Agriculture,
